39819961.review:
[h1]TL;DR? See Conclusion[/h1]

[h1]INTRODUCTION:[/h1]
Silent Storm is a 2003 real-time/turn-based tactical role-playing game developed by Nival Interactive. In 2004, an expansion for the game called Silent Storm: Sentinels was released. As of 2018 (the time of the writing of this review), both titles are included if you purchase Silent Storm: Gold Edition.

[h1]PLOT (No Spoilers):[/h1]
Silent Storm takes the player in an alternate universe during World War II. The year is 1943 and the war is raging across Europe. While the superpowers are busy fighting each other, a secret (and suspiciously well funded) world wide organization bent on world domination is making its move to ensure that ultimate victory will belong to them. The player will now have to assemble a multinational squad of elite soldiers (either Allied or Axis) to unravel the mystery behind this organization and foil their plan of establishing a new world order.

[h1]PROS:[/h1]
+ Good graphics that aged pretty well BUT.... (See Con #1 and #2);
+ Good character animations and level design;
+ Fun turn-based combat which transitions well into real-time mode once combat is concluded;
+ Good selection of musical scores that adds to the game's atmosphere;
+ Good story with a non-linear campaign (each new campaign is unique in some way);
+ Lengthy game time with multiple missions and several random encounter maps;
+ Good selection of weapons and ammo (each weapon making use of certain ammunition);
+ Good character progression system (skill tree) that allows to player to develop different play styles;
+ Great game mechanics that includes, but is not limited to:
[olist]
[*] Poses (run, walk, crouch, prone, strafe);
[*] Different firing modes for different guns (burst, full spray, snap shot, aimed shot, careful shot, and sniper shot);
[*] Spotting and Detection (example: your soldier knows that someone is hiding in that bush but he has no visibility on the target, this means that you can order him to empty a clip into the bush hoping that something dies);
[*] Cover system;
[*] Stealth mechanics; and
[*] Wounds and injuries that results in different negative conditions. Note that these can be removed by using certain medical tools.
[/olist]
+ Great implementation of destructible terrain that can change the player's play style and strategy;
+ The game's difficulty is fairly challenging;
+ Nice selection of unique squadmates that can be recruited to your team; and
+ Excellent implementation of the 'chance to hit' mechanic – If your soldier only has a 10% chance to hit, then each bullet fired will have a 10% chance of hitting the target. This is unlike XCOM: Enemy Unknown's system where either all bullets hit or none of them hits.

[h1]CONS:[/h1]
- Unpatched graphics bug that removes ambient occlusion, shadows, and reflections (can be resolved by this [url=http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=387716971]mod[/url];
- The game's performance takes a hit if you mod the game to fix the shadow bug (See Con #1);
- Over abundance in ammo takes the fun out of scavenging for ammo and weapons during lengthy missions;
- VIP and Civilian AI are suicidal;
- Enemy AI turn takes too long to resolve;
- How to use medical and engineering tools is not fully explained;
- Throw range of grenades and grenade explosion area-of-effect are severely limited; and
- No Multiplayer.

[h1]NEUTRAL:[/h1]
+/- The Sci-Fi elements somewhat ruins the nice World War II setting of the game (and it definitely ruins late game balance); and
+/- Very hammy, over-the-top and cheesy voice acting.

[h1]CONCLUSION:[/h1]
Silent Storm is a [b]GREAT GAME[/b] and is [b]HIGHLY RECOMMENDED[/b] for turn-based strategy fans. Despite its age, the gameplay, as well as its visuals, has aged pretty well. This game has a good blend of tactical-depth, good visuals, atmosphere, and story. Although it might have shot itself in the foot with the addition of some Sci-Fi elements, it does not, in any way, ruin the overall experience.

[h1]WORTH IT?[/h1]
The current price for the Gold Edition of the game is USD$ 9.99 (or your regional equivalent) and is well worth it for any turn-based strategy fan. 

[h1]FINAL NOTES:[/h1]
I wish XCOM: Enemy Unknown and Enemy Within implemented Silent Storm's 'chance to hit' mechanic since the latter's mechanic is more authentic in its approach.
